Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER-NAMED SYS_* SENTINELS (Win32 routing markers)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Windows does not expose a stable user-mode Unix-style syscall number table.
NT syscall numbers (the values that the `syscall` instruction on x86_64
Windows places in RAX to select an SSDT entry, or that `int 0x2e` placed
in EAX on pre-x86_64 Windows) shift between Windows versions, service
packs, and even between cumulative updates. Microsoft's supported user-mode
contract is the Win32 API exported by `kernel32.dll`, `ntdll.dll`, and the
sibling system DLLs; the kernel ABI is intentionally undocumented and
unstable. Source: Geoff Chappell's NT-syscall database (https://www.geoffchappell.com/studies/windows/win32/ntdll/api/native/index.htm)
documents the per-build drift of syscall numbers across Windows 7, 8, 10,
11, and Server SKUs; Microsoft Docs `Windows-Kernel-Documentation` reiterates
that the syscall table is not part of the supported user-mode contract.

The cross-platform dispatcher's `SYS_<NAME>` bare-name surface exists so
non-Windows targets can encode a numeric syscall constant for inline-asm
routing. On Windows, those numbers are meaningless: the `syscall_<name>`
wrappers in this file bypass the number entirely and route through the
Win32 `api_<operation>` wrappers (`api_read_file`, `api_create_file`,
`api_virtual_alloc`, etc.) which target the documented stable DLL exports.

Per P2-B Decision 4, each `SYS_<NAME>` Process on Windows returns the
sentinel value `-1` (INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE-equivalent). The sentinel is
intentional: any caller that attempts to use this value as a numeric
syscall argument (e.g. passing it to `syscall_3`) will receive a guaranteed
syscall failure (-1 is reserved by every Unix-ABI kernel as an invalid
syscall index, returning -ENOSYS or terminating the process per platform
policy). This converts a silent mis-route into a loud, debuggable failure
mode that surfaces immediately during cross-target testing.

The real entry point for each operation on Windows is the corresponding
`api_<operation>` wrapper, not the SYS_ constant. Callers writing
portable code should use the `syscall_<name>` form (e.g. `syscall_read`),
which the dispatcher routes through `windows_x86_64_syscall_read` once
Wave 2 lands; that wrapper then calls `api_read_file` with the correct
Win64 ABI. Callers that hardcode `SYS_READ` will receive -1, which is
the intended dispatcher-incompatibility signal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each `SYS_<NAME>` Process is a nullary Integer-returning accessor that
unconditionally returns `-1`. The compiler will inline these to a constant
at every call site; there is no runtime computation, no DLL lookup, and
no kernel transition. The sentinel value is selected to match the Linux
ABI's "invalid syscall index" convention (kernel `arch/x86/entry/syscall_64.c`
treats negative `__NR_*` values as out-of-range and returns -ENOSYS),
so any portable caller that tries to feed the value through a Linux-style
`syscall_N(SYS_X, ...)` ladder will observe a clean error rather than
undefined behaviour.

Wave 2 will rename these to the prefixed form `windows_x86_64_SYS_READ`,
etc., to match the dispatcher's prefix-based routing pattern; Wave 1
preserves the bare name to match the still-bare dispatcher.

The set of 27 names is the dispatcher's declared SYS_* surface from the
P2-B design doc "Per-platform syscall inventory" section:
SYS_READ, SYS_WRITE, SYS_OPEN, SYS_CLOSE, SYS_EXIT, SYS_EXIT_GROUP,
SYS_BRK, SYS_MMAP, SYS_MUNMAP, SYS_STAT, SYS_FSTAT, SYS_LSTAT, SYS_LSEEK,
SYS_CREAT, SYS_UNLINK, SYS_MKDIR, SYS_RMDIR, SYS_GETPID, SYS_GETPPID,
SYS_GETUID, SYS_GETGID, SYS_GETEUID, SYS_GETEGID, SYS_GETCWD, SYS_CHDIR,
SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME, SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; the compiler inlines them at every call site. Zero
runtime cost. Do not introduce any computation, DLL probe, or version
check here; the sentinel is intentionally version-invariant. The Win32
API routing performed by `api_<operation>` wrappers handles all dynamic
binding at the documented-DLL-export layer.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a constant `-1` carries no security state and exposes no
information about the running Windows version. The sentinel does not
reveal whether the host is Windows 7, 10, 11, or a Server SKU; this
prevents version-fingerprinting attacks through the syscall-number
surface.

Callers MUST NOT pass this value to any Win32 API as a syscall index
or handle: -1 is `INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE` in the Win32 handle domain, and
passing it to functions like `ReadFile` or `CloseHandle` produces
ERROR_INVALID_HANDLE (6) with no kernel-side side effect. The portable
`syscall_<name>` wrappers in this file already perform the correct Win32
API routing and do not consult these SYS_ constants.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_SYS_READ" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows sentinel - real entry point is api_read_file
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_SYS_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows sentinel - real entry point is api_write_file
End Process

