Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER FILE-ACCESS FLAGS (synthesized Win32 equivalents)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform dispatcher exposes Unix-style `O_*` open-flag constants
(O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY, O_RDWR, O_CREAT, O_TRUNC, O_APPEND) so portable
code can request file access modes without knowing the host OS. On
Linux/BSD/Darwin these are POSIX-defined small integers (O_RDONLY=0,
O_WRONLY=1, etc.) packed into the second argument of `open(2)`. On
Windows, the equivalent concepts are split across three CreateFileW
parameters: `dwDesiredAccess` (read/write capability), `dwCreationDisposition`
(create/open/truncate semantics), and `dwFlagsAndAttributes` (append/etc.).

Per P2-B Decision 4 and design doc Section "Constants per platform"
(Windows synthesis paragraph), each `O_<NAME>` Process on Windows returns
the Win32 dwDesiredAccess bit or a synthetic disposition flag. The
caller of `syscall_open` decodes these synthetic flags and maps them
onto CreateFileW's parameter set. Concrete mapping:

- O_RDONLY = 0x80000000 (GENERIC_READ from winnt.h)
- O_WRONLY = 0x40000000 (GENERIC_WRITE from winnt.h)
- O_RDWR   = 0xC0000000 (GENERIC_READ | GENERIC_WRITE composite)
- O_CREAT  = 1 (synthetic flag; the syscall_open wrapper maps to CREATE_ALWAYS dwCreationDisposition when set together with O_TRUNC, OPEN_ALWAYS when set alone)
- O_TRUNC  = 2 (synthetic flag; OR'd with O_CREAT yields CREATE_ALWAYS; alone yields TRUNCATE_EXISTING)
- O_APPEND = 4 (synthetic flag; the wrapper performs a manual SetFilePointerEx to file-end before each write since CreateFileW has no native FILE_APPEND_DATA-only disposition)

Source: Microsoft Win32 API documentation
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/fileapi/nf-fileapi-createfilew),
`winnt.h` constants GENERIC_READ (0x80000000) and GENERIC_WRITE
(0x40000000). The synthetic flags (1, 2, 4) are chosen so the high-order
bits remain distinct from the dwDesiredAccess high bits, allowing a
single Integer to carry both pieces of information.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each `O_<NAME>` Process is a nullary Integer accessor returning the
constant. The values are sized to be representable as Runa Integer
(64-bit signed); the high bits of GENERIC_READ/GENERIC_WRITE encode
naturally since Runa Integer is wider than the Win32 DWORD (32-bit
unsigned) used by CreateFileW. The `syscall_open` wrapper extracts
the low-bit synthetic flags (O_CREAT/O_TRUNC/O_APPEND) via bitwise AND
and the high-bit access flags (GENERIC_READ/GENERIC_WRITE) directly.

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_O_RDONLY`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; inlined at every call site. The wrapper that decodes
these into CreateFileW arguments performs at most three bitwise
operations (AND/OR/test) per flag, which is negligible compared to the
kernel-mode I/O cost of the actual file operation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file-access-mode constant carries no security state. The
synthetic mapping does not weaken the Win32 ACL model: CreateFileW
still consults the file's DACL against the calling token regardless of
which Unix-style `O_*` flags the caller passed. Callers requesting
`O_RDWR` on a file with read-only ACL receive ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED (5)
identically to the Unix `EACCES` outcome on Linux/BSD.

Callers using `O_CREAT` MUST specify an appropriate `mode` argument
(MODE_0644 or MODE_0755) to express the intended permission; Windows
maps these onto inherited-DACL semantics rather than POSIX mode bits,
but the cross-platform dispatcher contract still requires the mode
argument to be provided.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_O_RDONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 2147483648  Note: GENERIC_READ (0x80000000) - read-only access on Windows
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_O_WRONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 1073741824  Note: GENERIC_WRITE (0x40000000) - write-only access on Windows
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_O_RDWR" returns Integer:
    Return 3221225472  Note: GENERIC_READ|GENERIC_WRITE (0xC0000000) - read/write access on Windows
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_O_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Synthetic flag - syscall_open maps to CREATE_ALWAYS / OPEN_ALWAYS dwCreationDisposition
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_O_TRUNC" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Synthetic flag - syscall_open maps to TRUNCATE_EXISTING when alone, CREATE_ALWAYS when with O_CREAT
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_O_APPEND" returns Integer:
    Return 4  Note: Synthetic flag - syscall_open performs manual SetFilePointerEx to end-of-file before each write
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name
API. On Unix platforms these are octal permission triplets (0644 =
rw-r--r--, 0755 = rwxr-xr-x). Windows has no POSIX mode-bit concept;
file permissions are expressed through Discretionary Access Control
Lists (DACLs) attached as ACEs in the file's SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR.

Per P2-B Decision 4 Windows synthesis policy, these constants return
the decimal equivalents of the Unix octal values (420 = 0644 octal,
493 = 0755 octal) for cross-platform contract compatibility. Windows
callers that pass these values into `api_create_file` will see the
mode argument silently ignored by CreateFileW (which does not accept
a POSIX mode_t); the file is instead created with permissions inherited
from the parent directory's DACL.

Source: Linux `include/uapi/linux/stat.h` defines the octal-decimal
mapping (S_IRUSR=0400=256, S_IWUSR=0200=128, etc.); 0644 = 420,
0755 = 493. Microsoft Win32 documentation for CreateFileW
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/fileapi/nf-fileapi-createfilew)
shows the `lpSecurityAttributes` parameter as the explicit DACL
override path on Windows.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each Process is a nullary accessor returning the constant. Cross-platform
code that uses these constants gets the same numeric value on every
target, which means file-creation calls compile identically regardless
of target OS. The platform-specific interpretation happens inside
the corresponding `syscall_open` wrapper.

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_MODE_0644`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined. Zero runtime cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The mode value is informational on Windows: CreateFileW does not
consume it. Callers that need a specific DACL on a newly-created file
on Windows MUST construct a SECURITY_ATTRIBUTES structure with the
desired SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR and pass it as the `lpSecurityAttributes`
argument to `api_create_file`; the mode constants returned here are
not sufficient to enforce a specific DACL.

For cross-platform code: setting MODE_0644 on a file communicates
"world-readable, owner-writable" intent. On Linux/BSD this becomes
the actual permission bits; on Windows the file inherits the parent
directory's DACL. The semantic divergence is documented per-call-site
by callers that need precise control.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r-- (informational on Windows; CreateFileW uses inherited DACLs)
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x (informational on Windows; CreateFileW uses inherited DACLs)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER MEMORY-PROTECTION FLAGS (synthesized Win32 equivalents)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Unix `mmap(2)`/`mprotect(2)` accept a `prot` argument composed of
PROT_NONE/PROT_READ/PROT_WRITE/PROT_EXEC bit flags (Linux:
PROT_READ=0x1, PROT_WRITE=0x2, PROT_EXEC=0x4). Windows
VirtualAlloc/VirtualProtect use a different model: a single
flProtect DWORD selecting one of ~14 page-protection constants
(PAGE_NOACCESS=0x01, PAGE_READONLY=0x02, PAGE_READWRITE=0x04,
PAGE_EXECUTE=0x10, etc.). Source: `winnt.h` Memory Protection
Constants (https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/Memory/memory-protection-constants).

Per P2-B Decision 4, the cross-platform `PROT_*` dispatcher constants
on Windows return the closest single-protection Win32 PAGE_* value
so a portable `syscall_mprotect(addr, len, prot)` call routes through
`api_virtual_protect` correctly. The mapping is:

- PROT_NONE  = 0x01 (PAGE_NOACCESS - no access permitted)
- PROT_READ  = 0x02 (PAGE_READONLY - read access only)
- PROT_WRITE = 0x04 (PAGE_READWRITE - read+write; Windows has no write-only)
- PROT_EXEC  = 0x10 (PAGE_EXECUTE - execute-only)

Note that Unix allows PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC composition via
bitwise OR; Windows requires the caller to pick one of the composite
PAGE_EXECUTE_READ (0x20) / PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE (0x40) explicitly.
The cross-platform `syscall_mprotect` wrapper performs the OR-then-map
transformation, so callers get the correct Win32 PAGE_* even when
composing flags portably (e.g. PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE = 6 maps to
PAGE_READWRITE = 4).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each Process is a nullary Integer accessor returning the Win32
PAGE_* equivalent. The values are chosen so a single-bit Unix-style
`prot` value maps unambiguously to a Win32 PAGE_* constant via the
syscall wrapper's lookup table. Composite Unix `prot` values are
decomposed by the wrapper before mapping.

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_PROT_NONE`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; inlined. The mapping logic in `syscall_mprotect`
adds at most a handful of comparisons per call - negligible against
the kernel-mode page-table update cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Page-protection flags have direct security implications. Callers MUST
follow W^X (write XOR execute) discipline: do not request
PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC simultaneously on the same mapping
unless absolutely required (e.g. JIT-compiled code). On Windows the
W^X-violating request maps to PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE (0x40), which
Microsoft's CFG (Control Flow Guard) and Process Mitigation Policies
flag as a security risk. Prefer the two-step pattern: allocate with
PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, write content, then mprotect to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC.

PROT_NONE pages are useful for guard pages between stacks/heaps;
accessing them raises an access-violation exception on Windows
(STATUS_ACCESS_VIOLATION = 0xC0000005), which the caller can handle
via SEH (__try/__except in C; equivalent in Runa).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_PROT_NONE" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: PAGE_NOACCESS - no read/write/execute
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_PROT_READ" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: PAGE_READONLY - read-only access
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_PROT_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return 4  Note: PAGE_READWRITE - Windows has no write-only; uses read+write
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_PROT_EXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: PAGE_EXECUTE - execute-only access
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER MEMORY-MAPPING FLAGS (synthesized Win32 equivalents)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Unix `mmap(2)` accepts a `flags` argument with MAP_SHARED, MAP_PRIVATE,
MAP_FIXED, MAP_ANONYMOUS bits. Windows VirtualAlloc has no direct
parallel; instead it splits the use case across two API families:
file-backed mappings use `CreateFileMapping` + `MapViewOfFile`,
anonymous mappings use plain `VirtualAlloc` with MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE.

Per P2-B Decision 4, the cross-platform `MAP_*` dispatcher constants
on Windows return synthetic values that the `syscall_mmap` wrapper
decodes into the appropriate Win32 API path:

- MAP_SHARED    = 0x4000000 (SEC_COMMIT for CreateFileMapping's flProtect
                  high-bits; signals shared file-backed mapping)
- MAP_PRIVATE   = 0 (no special flag - VirtualAlloc is private by
                  default; CreateFileMapping uses PAGE_READONLY for
                  copy-on-write semantics)
- MAP_FIXED     = 1 (synthetic - signals syscall_mmap to use
                  MapViewOfFileEx with explicit base address, or
                  VirtualAlloc(addr, ...) with MEM_RESERVE for the
                  exact address)
- MAP_ANONYMOUS = 0x40 (PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE - signals VirtualAlloc
                  path with no underlying file; the value collides
                  intentionally with PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE because
                  VirtualAlloc-for-JIT is the dominant MAP_ANONYMOUS
                  use case)

Source: Microsoft Win32 documentation for VirtualAlloc
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/memoryapi/nf-memoryapi-virtualalloc),
CreateFileMappingW
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/winbase/nf-winbase-createfilemappingw),
and MapViewOfFileEx
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/memoryapi/nf-memoryapi-mapviewoffileex).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each Process is a nullary Integer accessor returning the synthetic
flag. The `syscall_mmap` wrapper decodes the flag combination and
selects the Win32 API path:
- (flags & MAP_ANONYMOUS) != 0 → VirtualAlloc(addr, len, MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE, prot)
- (flags & MAP_ANONYMOUS) == 0 → CreateFileMapping(fd, ..., SEC_COMMIT if MAP_SHARED, PAGE_READONLY if MAP_PRIVATE) then MapViewOfFile/MapViewOfFileEx

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_MAP_SHARED`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; inlined. The wrapper's API-selection logic is at
most a few comparisons. The kernel-side cost (page-table updates,
section-object creation) dwarfs any wrapper overhead.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
MAP_SHARED mappings create cross-process shared memory on Unix; on
Windows the equivalent is a named file-mapping object (via
`CreateFileMappingW` with a non-NULL lpName). Callers MUST scope the
mapping name with the appropriate session/namespace prefix (`Local\`,
`Global\`) to prevent unintended cross-session sharing on
multi-user/Terminal-Server hosts.

MAP_ANONYMOUS with PROT_EXEC (i.e. JIT allocation) is a W^X violation
that triggers Process Mitigation Policy alerts; see PROT_EXEC
@Security_Scope above.

MAP_FIXED can overlay existing mappings on Unix (silently unmapping
them). On Windows, MapViewOfFileEx with an in-use base address
returns NULL with ERROR_INVALID_ADDRESS (487); the wrapper does
not silently unmap. Callers requiring overlay semantics must
explicitly `api_virtual_free` the existing region first.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 67108864  Note: 0x4000000 (SEC_COMMIT) - signals CreateFileMapping shared path
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: VirtualAlloc default is private; CreateFileMapping uses PAGE_READONLY for copy-on-write
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Synthetic - signals syscall_mmap to use MapViewOfFileEx with explicit base or VirtualAlloc at exact address
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 64  Note: PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE (0x40) - signals VirtualAlloc path with MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` on Unix and `SetFilePointerEx`'s
`dwMoveMethod` on Windows are numerically identical: SEEK_SET = 0 =
FILE_BEGIN, SEEK_CUR = 1 = FILE_CURRENT, SEEK_END = 2 = FILE_END.
This is a rare case of cross-platform value coincidence; the values
were standardised in the original POSIX specification and Microsoft
chose matching values for the Win32 API to ease porting.

Source: POSIX.1-2017 `<unistd.h>` SEEK_* constants; Microsoft Win32
documentation for SetFilePointerEx
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/fileapi/nf-fileapi-setfilepointerex)
shows FILE_BEGIN/FILE_CURRENT/FILE_END as 0/1/2 in `winbase.h`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each Process is a nullary Integer accessor. The values match both the
Unix SEEK_* and Win32 FILE_* values, so the `syscall_lseek` wrapper
can pass them verbatim to SetFilePointerEx without translation.

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_SEEK_SET`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; inlined. The values pass through to SetFilePointerEx
unmodified, so the wrapper adds zero translation overhead.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a whence constant carries no security state. Callers passing
user-influenced `offset` values into `syscall_lseek` MUST validate the
resulting absolute file position; SetFilePointerEx with a negative
offset and FILE_BEGIN sets the file pointer to a negative value, which
subsequent ReadFile/WriteFile calls reject with ERROR_NEGATIVE_SEEK (131).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: FILE_BEGIN - seek from start of file
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: FILE_CURRENT - seek from current position
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: FILE_END - seek from end of file
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STANDARD STREAM FILE DESCRIPTOR CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Unix exposes the three standard streams as the file descriptors 0
(stdin), 1 (stdout), 2 (stderr). Windows uses three standard handles
acquired via `GetStdHandle(STD_INPUT_HANDLE|STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE|STD_ERROR_HANDLE)`
where the input values are the negative integers -10, -11, -12.

Per P2-B Decision 4 Windows synthesis policy, the cross-platform
STDIN_FILENO/STDOUT_FILENO/STDERR_FILENO constants on Windows return
the GetStdHandle parameter values (-10/-11/-12), not the Unix
descriptor numbers (0/1/2). This way the `syscall_read`/`syscall_write`
wrappers on Windows can route a portable `STDOUT_FILENO` constant
straight to `api_get_std_handle` without additional translation.

Source: Microsoft Win32 documentation for GetStdHandle
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processenv/nf-processenv-getstdhandle):
STD_INPUT_HANDLE = -10 ((DWORD)-10), STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE = -11,
STD_ERROR_HANDLE = -12. These values are defined in `winbase.h`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each Process is a nullary Integer accessor returning the GetStdHandle
parameter value. The Windows `syscall_read` wrapper detects these
negative sentinel values and routes through `api_get_std_handle` to
materialise the real HANDLE before calling `api_read_file`. Real Win32
file HANDLE values are always positive (or INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE = -1),
so the negative-sentinel discrimination is unambiguous.

Wave 2 will rename to `windows_x86_64_STDIN_FILENO`, etc.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; inlined. The wrapper's sentinel-detection adds one
sign-test per call; the subsequent `GetStdHandle` lookup is a single
DLL function call that Microsoft documents as essentially-free
(returns a per-process cached handle from the PEB's ProcessParameters).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The standard handles are inherited from the parent process by default.
Callers running in restricted-token contexts (e.g. AppContainer) may
find that GetStdHandle returns INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE for one or more
streams; the `syscall_read`/`syscall_write` wrappers MUST check for
INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE before issuing api_read_file/api_write_file.

In services or non-console processes, the standard handles may be
NULL or refer to a closed file; portable code using these constants
should not assume the streams exist. The behaviour matches POSIX
where init-time stream closure leaves descriptors 0/1/2 invalid.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_STDIN_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -10  Note: STD_INPUT_HANDLE - parameter for GetStdHandle to acquire stdin
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_STDOUT_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -11  Note: STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE - parameter for GetStdHandle to acquire stdout
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_STDERR_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -12  Note: STD_ERROR_HANDLE - parameter for GetStdHandle to acquire stderr
End Process

