Note: ============================================================================
Note: P2-B EXTENDED WIN32 API WRAPPERS (process / thread / timing primitives)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The P2-B cross-platform threading + syscall design (Decision 4) requires
Windows-side wrappers for `CreateThread`, `WaitForSingleObject`,
`ResumeThread`, `TerminateThread`, `OpenProcess`,
`QueryPerformanceCounter`, and `QueryPerformanceFrequency`. These map
onto the `platform_thread_create`, `platform_thread_join`,
`platform_thread_yield`, `platform_thread_exit`, and clock-precision
primitives that P2-B.2 (cross-platform threading) will lower to per
this file's exports.

Each wrapper follows the established Win64 calling convention
documented in this file's header:
- First four integer/pointer arguments in RCX, RDX, R8, R9
- Fifth argument and beyond in stack slots (8-byte each)
- 32-byte shadow space mandatory below the call site for callee's RCX/RDX/R8/R9 spill
- RAX holds the return value
- RCX, RDX, R8, R9, R10, R11 are volatile (caller-saved); RBX, RBP, RDI, RSI, R12-R15 are non-volatile

Source: Microsoft x64 calling convention documentation
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/x64-calling-convention),
plus the individual API references for kernel32!CreateThread
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-createthread),
kernel32!WaitForSingleObject
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-waitforsingleobject),
kernel32!ResumeThread
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-resumethread),
kernel32!TerminateThread
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-terminatethread),
kernel32!OpenProcess
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-openprocess),
kernel32!QueryPerformanceCounter
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/profileapi/nf-profileapi-queryperformancecounter),
kernel32!QueryPerformanceFrequency
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/profileapi/nf-profileapi-queryperformancefrequency).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper exposes a Runa Process with explicit Integer arguments and
return type matching the underlying DWORD/HANDLE/BOOL of the Win32
prototype (Runa Integer is wide enough to carry any 64-bit DWORD or
HANDLE without truncation).

The body uses Inline Assembly to lower the Runa call into the Win64
ABI. The assembly is structured as: spill named-parameter stack slots
into RCX/RDX/R8/R9 and the on-stack argument area; reserve 32-byte
shadow space; emit `call <symbol>` targeting the PE import thunk that
the Runa linker resolves against kernel32.dll's import library; on
return, materialise RAX back into the Runa result slot.

The new wrappers below use Win64-correct inline assembly (RCX/RDX/R8/R9
plus 32-byte shadow space plus `call <symbol>` targeting kernel32.dll's
PE import thunk) rather than the ARM64-shaped assembly that the sibling
api_create_file/api_read_file/etc. inherited from the pre-Decision-5
windows_arm64 source. The structural template (Inline Assembly block
with explicit stack-slot loads, call site, and result spill) matches
the file's existing api_* layout so the v0.0.8.8 FFI lowering pass
retargets every body uniformly from inline-asm to a synthesised
dlopen-equivalent runtime binding. The Runa-level interface remains
stable across that retargeting; only the assembly bodies change.

Wave 2 will rename these to `windows_x86_64_api_create_thread`, etc.,
to match the prefix-routing dispatcher pattern.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The cost of each wrapper is dominated by the Win32 API kernel-transition
(for CreateThread/WaitForSingleObject) or system-cache lookup
(for QueryPerformanceCounter, which Microsoft documents as a single
RDTSCP or HPET read on modern systems). The Runa-level marshalling
overhead is a handful of register loads plus the call; negligible
against kernel-mode work.

QueryPerformanceCounter is documented as the recommended high-resolution
timer on Windows since Windows XP; it has nanosecond-class resolution
on systems with invariant-TSC support (every CPU sold since Nehalem/Bulldozer).
Use this in preference to GetTickCount or timeGetTime for any timing
that needs better than ~10ms granularity. Frequency is constant across
the process lifetime; cache the result of api_query_performance_frequency
in a one-time-init slot rather than calling it per measurement.

CreateThread's stack-size argument (RDX = dwStackSize) of 0 uses the
PE header's `SizeOfStackReserve` default (typically 1 MiB). Callers
creating many threads should pass an explicit reduced size (e.g. 64 KiB)
plus dwCreationFlags = STACK_SIZE_PARAM_IS_A_RESERVATION (0x10000)
to avoid VAD-region exhaustion on 32-bit Windows hosts.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
CreateThread inherits the caller's process token and runs the
lpStartAddress code with the caller's full privilege set. Callers MUST
ensure lpStartAddress points to validated, sanitised code; passing
a function pointer derived from untrusted input is a remote-code-execution
vector. The lpParameter (R9 in Win64) is a single LPVOID delivered to
the thread entry; complex argument lists must be packed into a
caller-allocated struct, and the caller is responsible for the
allocator/deallocator handshake (the thread cannot signal completion
to the parent until it explicitly does so).

WaitForSingleObject blocks the calling thread; passing
dwMilliseconds = INFINITE (0xFFFFFFFF) is the canonical "wait until
signalled" pattern. Specify a finite timeout to allow recovery from
a hung or terminated peer thread.

OpenProcess with PROCESS_TERMINATE (0x0001) is the minimum-privilege
combination needed to call TerminateProcess; do not request
PROCESS_ALL_ACCESS (0x1FFFFF) unless you genuinely need full debug
access to the target. The Process Mitigation Policy framework can
restrict OpenProcess to ProtectedProcessLight targets; callers must
handle ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED (5) gracefully.

TerminateThread is documented by Microsoft as DANGEROUS: it does not
release locks held by the thread, does not free its DLL-thread-attach
notifications, and can leave the process in an inconsistent state.
Use only as a last resort when the thread cannot be cooperatively
signalled to exit.

QueryPerformanceCounter exposes a hardware counter; it does not leak
process-confidential information. Frequency information (api_query_performance_frequency)
is also not sensitive.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_api_open_process" takes desired_access as Integer, inherit_handle as Integer, process_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenProcess - Open handle to existing process
    Note: desired_access: PROCESS_TERMINATE (0x0001), PROCESS_QUERY_INFORMATION (0x0400), etc.
    Note: inherit_handle: TRUE if child processes inherit this handle, FALSE otherwise
    Note: process_id: target process PID from GetCurrentProcessId on the target side
    Note: Returns: HANDLE to opened process, or 0 (NULL) on failure
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=desired_access, RDX=inherit_handle, R8=process_id

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load parameters into Win64 ABI registers
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # desired_access (1st arg)
        mov rdx, [rsp+16]      # inherit_handle (2nd arg)
        mov r8,  [rsp+24]      # process_id (3rd arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space (Win64 ABI requirement)
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call OpenProcess from kernel32.dll via PE import thunk
        call OpenProcess

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store HANDLE result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_create_thread" takes thread_attributes as Integer, stack_size as Integer, start_address as Integer, parameter as Integer, creation_flags as Integer, thread_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: CreateThread - Create new thread in calling process
    Note: thread_attributes: LPSECURITY_ATTRIBUTES (NULL = default), passed in RCX
    Note: stack_size: SIZE_T initial stack reservation (0 = use PE header default), passed in RDX
    Note: start_address: LPTHREAD_START_ROUTINE function pointer, passed in R8
    Note: parameter: LPVOID argument delivered to start_address, passed in R9
    Note: creation_flags: DWORD CREATE_SUSPENDED (0x4)/STACK_SIZE_PARAM_IS_A_RESERVATION (0x10000)/0, on stack [rsp+32]
    Note: thread_id: LPDWORD receives created thread ID (NULL = don't return), on stack [rsp+40]
    Note: Returns: HANDLE to new thread (NULL on failure)
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX, RDX, R8, R9 for first four args; [rsp+32] and [rsp+40] for fifth and sixth

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Marshal parameters into Win64 ABI registers
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # thread_attributes
        mov rdx, [rsp+16]      # stack_size
        mov r8,  [rsp+24]      # start_address
        mov r9,  [rsp+32]      # parameter

        # Reserve 48-byte stack: 32-byte shadow space + 16 bytes for two on-stack args
        sub rsp, 48

        # Place 5th and 6th args at [rsp+32] and [rsp+40] (above shadow space)
        mov rax, [rsp+88]      # creation_flags (caller frame [rsp+40] before sub rsp, 48)
        mov [rsp+32], rax
        mov rax, [rsp+96]      # thread_id (caller frame [rsp+48] before sub rsp, 48)
        mov [rsp+40], rax

        # Call CreateThread from kernel32.dll via PE import thunk
        call CreateThread

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 48

        # Store HANDLE result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_wait_for_single_object" takes object_handle as Integer, milliseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: WaitForSingleObject - Block until handle is signalled or timeout elapses
    Note: object_handle: HANDLE to wait on (thread, event, mutex, semaphore, etc.)
    Note: milliseconds: DWORD timeout; INFINITE (0xFFFFFFFF = -1) for no timeout
    Note: Returns: WAIT_OBJECT_0 (0) on signal, WAIT_TIMEOUT (0x102) on timeout, WAIT_ABANDONED (0x80) for orphaned mutex, WAIT_FAILED (0xFFFFFFFF) on error
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=object_handle, RDX=milliseconds

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load parameters into Win64 ABI registers
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # object_handle (1st arg)
        mov rdx, [rsp+16]      # milliseconds (2nd arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call WaitForSingleObject from kernel32.dll
        call WaitForSingleObject

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store DWORD result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_resume_thread" takes thread_handle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ResumeThread - Decrement thread suspend count; thread runs when count reaches 0
    Note: thread_handle: HANDLE returned by CreateThread with CREATE_SUSPENDED, or earlier SuspendThread call
    Note: Returns: previous suspend count, or 0xFFFFFFFF (-1 as DWORD) on failure
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=thread_handle

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load parameter into RCX
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # thread_handle (1st arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call ResumeThread from kernel32.dll
        call ResumeThread

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store DWORD result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_terminate_thread" takes thread_handle as Integer, exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: TerminateThread - Forcibly terminate thread; DANGEROUS (does not release locks/cleanup TLS)
    Note: thread_handle: HANDLE to thread to terminate
    Note: exit_code: DWORD value the thread's GetExitCodeThread will report
    Note: Returns: BOOL TRUE (nonzero) on success, FALSE (0) on failure
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=thread_handle, RDX=exit_code

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load parameters into Win64 ABI registers
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # thread_handle (1st arg)
        mov rdx, [rsp+16]      # exit_code (2nd arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call TerminateThread from kernel32.dll
        call TerminateThread

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store BOOL result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_query_performance_counter" takes performance_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: QueryPerformanceCounter - Retrieve current high-resolution performance counter
    Note: performance_count: pointer to LARGE_INTEGER (8-byte signed) that receives the counter
    Note: Returns: BOOL TRUE on success; documented as always succeeding since Windows XP
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=performance_count

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load pointer into RCX
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # performance_count (LPLARGE_INTEGER, 1st arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call QueryPerformanceCounter from kernel32.dll
        call QueryPerformanceCounter

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store BOOL result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_api_query_performance_frequency" takes frequency as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: QueryPerformanceFrequency - Retrieve counter frequency (ticks per second)
    Note: frequency: pointer to LARGE_INTEGER that receives the frequency (constant for process lifetime)
    Note: Returns: BOOL TRUE on success; FALSE only on pre-XP systems lacking a high-resolution counter
    Note: Win64 ABI: RCX=frequency

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load pointer into RCX
        mov rcx, [rsp+8]       # frequency (LPLARGE_INTEGER, 1st arg)

        # Reserve 32-byte shadow space
        sub rsp, 32

        # Call QueryPerformanceFrequency from kernel32.dll
        call QueryPerformanceFrequency

        # Restore stack
        add rsp, 32

        # Store BOOL result from RAX
        mov [rsp-8], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIGH-LEVEL WRAPPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for ReadFile
    Note: fd: file handle (Windows uses handles, not file descriptors)
    Note: buffer: pointer to buffer
    Note: count: number of bytes to read
    Note: Returns: number of bytes read, or -1 on error
    
    Let bytes_read_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_read_file(fd, buffer, count, bytes_read_ptr, 0)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_read_ptr
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Let bytes_read be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with bytes_read_ptr, 0
    proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_read_ptr
    Return bytes_read
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for WriteFile
    Note: fd: file handle (Windows uses handles, not file descriptors)
    Note: buffer: pointer to buffer
    Note: count: number of bytes to write
    Note: Returns: number of bytes written, or -1 on error
    
    Let bytes_written_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_write_file(fd, buffer, count, bytes_written_ptr, 0)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_written_ptr
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Let bytes_written be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with bytes_written_ptr, 0
    proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_written_ptr
    Return bytes_written
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for CreateFileW
    Note: filename: pointer to wide string filename
    Note: flags: access flags (O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY, O_RDWR)
    Note: mode: creation mode (ignored on Windows)
    Note: Returns: file handle or -1 on error
    
    Let desired_access be 0
    Let share_mode be windows_x86_64_FILE_SHARE_READ plus windows_x86_64_FILE_SHARE_WRITE
    Let creation_disposition be windows_x86_64_OPEN_EXISTING
    Let flags_and_attributes be windows_x86_64_FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL
    
    If flags is equal to 0:
        Set desired_access to windows_x86_64_GENERIC_READ
    Otherwise If flags is equal to 1:
        Set desired_access to windows_x86_64_GENERIC_WRITE
    Otherwise If flags is equal to 2:
        Set desired_access to windows_x86_64_GENERIC_READ plus windows_x86_64_GENERIC_WRITE
    End If
    
    Let handle be windows_x86_64_api_create_file(filename, desired_access, share_mode, 0, creation_disposition, flags_and_attributes, 0)
    
    If handle is equal to windows_x86_64_INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return handle
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for CloseHandle
    Note: fd: file handle
    Note: Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_close_handle(fd)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for TerminateProcess
    Note: exit_code: exit code
    Note: Returns: never returns (process terminates)
    
    Let current_process be windows_x86_64_api_get_current_process()
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_terminate_process(current_process, exit_code)
    
    Return -1  Note: Should never reach here
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for VirtualAlloc
    Note: addr: preferred address or 0
    Note: length: size in bytes
    Note: prot: protection flags
    Note: flags: allocation flags (ignored)
    Note: fd: file descriptor (ignored)
    Note: offset: file offset (ignored)
    Note: Returns: pointer to allocated memory or -1 on error
    
    Let allocation_type be windows_x86_64_MEM_COMMIT
    Let protect be windows_x86_64_PAGE_READWRITE
    
    If prot is equal to 1:
        Set protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_READONLY
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 2:
        Set protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_READWRITE
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 4:
        Set protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE
    End If
    
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_virtual_alloc(addr, length, allocation_type, protect)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for VirtualFree
    Note: addr: pointer to memory
    Note: length: size in bytes (ignored, must be 0 for MEM_RELEASE)
    Note: Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_virtual_free(addr, 0, windows_x86_64_MEM_RELEASE)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_mprotect" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for VirtualProtect
    Note: addr: pointer to memory
    Note: length: size in bytes
    Note: prot: new protection flags
    Note: Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    
    Let old_protect_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let new_protect be windows_x86_64_PAGE_READWRITE
    
    If prot is equal to 1:
        Set new_protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_READONLY
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 2:
        Set new_protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_READWRITE
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 4:
        Set new_protect to windows_x86_64_PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE
    End If
    
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_virtual_protect(addr, length, new_protect, old_protect_ptr)
    proc memory_free from Memory with old_protect_ptr
    
    If result is equal to 0:
    Return -1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_getpid" returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for GetCurrentProcessId
    Note: Returns: process ID
    
    Return windows_x86_64_api_get_current_process_id()
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_kill" takes pid as Integer, sig as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: High-level wrapper for TerminateProcess
    Note: pid: process ID
    Note: sig: signal number (used as exit code)
    Note: Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error

    Note: Check if terminating current process
    If pid is equal to windows_x86_64_api_get_current_process_id():
        Let current_process be windows_x86_64_api_get_current_process()
        Let result be windows_x86_64_api_terminate_process(current_process, sig)
        Return -1  Note: Should never reach here
    End If

    Note: Terminating another process - use OpenProcess
    Note: PROCESS_TERMINATE = 0x0001
    Let desired_access be 1  Note: PROCESS_TERMINATE
    Let inherit_handle be 0  Note: FALSE

    Note: Call OpenProcess to get handle to target process
    Let process_handle be windows_x86_64_api_open_process(desired_access, inherit_handle, pid)
    If process_handle is equal to 0:
        Return -1  Note: Failed to open process (access denied or invalid PID)
    End If

    Note: Terminate the process with signal as exit code
    Let terminate_result be windows_x86_64_api_terminate_process(process_handle, sig)

    Note: Close process handle
    windows_x86_64_api_close_handle(process_handle)

    Note: Check if termination succeeded
    If terminate_result is equal to 0:
        Return -1  Note: TerminateProcess failed
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Success
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERIC SYSCALL_N SENTINELS (Win32 routing markers)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform dispatcher exposes seven generic `syscall_N` entry
points (arity 0..6) for inline-asm-driven Unix-style syscalls on
platforms that have a user-mode `syscall` or `svc`/`swi` opcode. Windows
has no stable user-mode equivalent: the NT syscall opcode (`syscall` on
x86_64, `int 0x2e` on x86) routes through a per-build dispatch table
whose entries shift across Windows versions, service packs, and
cumulative updates. Source: Microsoft Windows Internals 7e Part 1
(Russinovich, Solomon, Ionescu) Chapter 8 "System Mechanisms" documents
the SSDT layout and per-build drift.

Per P2-B Decision 4, each `syscall_N` Process on Windows returns the
sentinel value `-1` (matches the SYS_* sentinel pattern in this file).
Calling `syscall_N(syscall_num, ...)` on Windows with any number obtained
from this file's SYS_* accessors will receive -1-from-syscall-number
back (since the SYS_* accessors also return -1); this short-circuits
any portable code that tries to route a Linux syscall through the
generic dispatcher on a Windows target and surfaces the mis-route as
a deterministic -1 return.

The real Windows-side execution path for any operation goes through the
named `syscall_<name>` wrappers in this file (e.g. `syscall_read`,
`syscall_write`, `syscall_open`), which call `api_<operation>` and
issue Win32 API calls via the documented kernel32.dll exports.

Source: Microsoft x64 calling convention documentation
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/x64-calling-convention),
plus the syscall instruction reference in the AMD64 Architecture
Programmer's Manual Volume 3 (which documents `syscall` as a kernel-only
fast-call instruction on Windows where the user-mode opcode is not part
of the supported user-mode contract).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each `syscall_N` Process is an N+1-arity Integer accessor (1 for the
syscall number plus N args). On Windows, all such Processes
unconditionally return `-1`. The compiler will inline the constant
return when the call site's `syscall_number` argument is itself a
compile-time constant from this file's SYS_* set (since SYS_* are
constant-returning Processes that the compiler inlines, and `-1`
propagates trivially). When the call site uses a runtime-computed
syscall number, the wrapper still returns -1; Win32-side dispatch
requires a stable NT syscall table, which Microsoft does not provide
in any supported user-mode contract.

This implementation diverges from the Linux/BSD/MIPS/RISC-V/PowerPC
generic `syscall_N` bodies, which contain real inline assembly issuing
`syscall`/`svc`/`swi` with the syscall number in the convention-specific
register. The divergence is intentional and documented per P2-B
Decision 4: Windows callers must use the named `syscall_<name>` wrappers,
which route through Win32 API instead of the kernel-mode syscall opcode.

Wave 2 will rename these to `windows_x86_64_syscall_0`..
`windows_x86_64_syscall_6` to match the prefix-routing dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant `-1` returns; compiler-inlined. Zero runtime cost. The sentinel
is intentionally version-invariant; no DLL probe, no PE-import-thunk
resolution, no kernel transition.

Callers writing Windows-portable code MUST use the named
`syscall_<name>` wrappers (`syscall_read`, `syscall_write`, etc.) which
do the actual Win32 API work. The generic `syscall_N` accessors on
Windows exist solely for source-level dispatch-table compatibility;
they are not a performance path.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning `-1` carries no security state and leaks no information about
the host Windows version, build, or patch level. The sentinel is
deliberately uniform across all `syscall_N` accessors to prevent
side-channel inference of which platforms support which syscall arities.

Callers MUST NOT use `-1` as a real syscall return: it is the canonical
"this operation is unsupported on this platform" signal in this codebase
and any caller that proceeds as if `-1` were a valid result risks
misinterpreting an unsupported-operation as a "kernel returned -1 bytes
read", which on POSIX would be a hard error.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Windows sentinel - no user-mode syscall opcode; use syscall_<name> wrappers
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (additional Win32-routed entries)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform dispatcher requires `syscall_brk`, `syscall_fstat`,
and `syscall_lseek` to round out the ten `syscall_<name>` operations
(the other seven - read, write, open, close, exit, mmap, munmap - are
defined in the HIGH-LEVEL WRAPPER FUNCTIONS section above).

Routing on Windows per P2-B Decision 4 + Microsoft Win32 API documentation:

- `syscall_brk` adjusts the process's program break on Unix. Windows
  has no program-break concept; the equivalent dynamic memory growth
  is achieved via VirtualAlloc with MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE. The Windows
  wrapper routes through the existing `api_virtual_alloc` Win32 wrapper.
  Semantics: a non-zero addr argument requests a commit at that exact
  base address (VirtualAlloc returns the same address on success or
  NULL on failure, which the wrapper maps to -1). An addr of 0 queries
  effective break by requesting a small probe allocation and returning
  its base (this is the Windows equivalent of the Unix brk(0) "where
  is the heap top" query, since Windows has no shared per-process
  heap-top variable).

- `syscall_fstat` retrieves file metadata for an open file descriptor.
  Windows provides `GetFileInformationByHandle` (kernel32) which
  returns a BY_HANDLE_FILE_INFORMATION struct, plus `GetFileSizeEx`
  for size. This file does not currently expose a Win32 wrapper for
  these calls (the api_* set covers create/read/write/close/alloc/
  free/protect/terminate/std-handle/directory/delete plus the seven
  P2-B-added thread/timing wrappers, not stat). The wrapper therefore
  returns the sentinel `-1` to surface the cross-platform-fstat-via-
  dispatcher mis-route as a deterministic error. Windows-native code
  needing file metadata must call GetFileInformationByHandle through
  a dedicated stdlib path; portable Runa code should avoid fstat-like
  introspection in the dispatched syscall surface and use the
  filesystem-level abstractions instead.

- `syscall_lseek` repositions the file pointer. Windows provides
  `SetFilePointerEx` whose dwMoveMethod argument is value-compatible
  with the SEEK_* constants this file exposes. This file does not
  currently expose a Win32 wrapper for SetFilePointerEx (it is not in
  the api_* set above); the wrapper therefore returns `-1` to surface
  the mis-route deterministically. Portable callers needing seek
  semantics on Windows must use stdlib I/O abstractions that route
  through CreateFileW + SetFilePointerEx directly rather than relying
  on the dispatched syscall_lseek surface.

Source: Microsoft Win32 documentation for VirtualAlloc
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/memoryapi/nf-memoryapi-virtualalloc),
GetFileInformationByHandle
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/fileapi/nf-fileapi-getfileinformationbyhandle),
SetFilePointerEx
(https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/fileapi/nf-fileapi-setfilepointerex).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
- `syscall_brk` calls `api_virtual_alloc(addr, page_size, MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE,
  PAGE_READWRITE)`. MEM_COMMIT(0x1000)|MEM_RESERVE(0x2000) = 0x3000 = 12288.
  page_size is 4096 (the Windows x86_64 default page size from
  `GetSystemInfo().dwPageSize`). On success, VirtualAlloc returns the
  base address of the committed region (equal to addr if addr was
  page-aligned, or the system-chosen address if addr was 0).
  On failure (insufficient address space, working-set quota exceeded,
  invalid addr alignment) it returns NULL (0); the wrapper maps that
  to -1 to match the Unix brk() error convention.

- `syscall_fstat` returns -1; no Win32 binding for
  GetFileInformationByHandle exists in this file's api_* surface.

- `syscall_lseek` returns -1; no Win32 binding for SetFilePointerEx
  exists in this file's api_* surface.

Wave 2 will rename these to `windows_x86_64_syscall_brk`,
`windows_x86_64_syscall_fstat`, `windows_x86_64_syscall_lseek`.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
`syscall_brk` performs a single Win32 API call; the cost is dominated
by the kernel-side VAD-tree update inside the VirtualAlloc service.
For high-frequency dynamic allocation, callers should prefer the
process heap (HeapAlloc) or a stdlib allocator instead of looping
through brk; brk-style growth is an O(1) bulk operation suited to
infrequent large expansions.

`syscall_fstat` and `syscall_lseek` are constant -1 returns; inlined
by the compiler with zero runtime cost. Callers needing Windows-native
file metadata or seek operations should use the stdlib filesystem
abstractions which call CreateFileW + GetFileInformationByHandle /
SetFilePointerEx directly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
`syscall_brk` inherits VirtualAlloc's security model: the calling
token's working-set quota and any active Job Object memory limits
gate the allocation. Overrun returns ERROR_NOT_ENOUGH_MEMORY (8)
via api_virtual_alloc's NULL return. The wrapper does not request
PAGE_EXECUTE protection, so the committed region is writable-but-non-
executable, avoiding W^X violations.

`syscall_fstat` and `syscall_lseek` return -1 unconditionally on
Windows. The -1 sentinel carries no information about the host
filesystem, file ACL state, or open-handle table; cross-platform
attackers observing these returns cannot infer anything Windows-
specific from the value.

Callers MUST NOT use `-1` as a real syscall return; it is the
documented "operation not exposed on this Windows binding" signal
in this codebase. Any caller proceeding as if -1 were a valid result
risks misinterpreting the sentinel as a "kernel returned -1 bytes"
which on POSIX would be a hard error.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust program break (Unix concept); Windows synthesizes via VirtualAlloc
    Note: MEM_COMMIT|MEM_RESERVE = 0x1000|0x2000 = 12288; PAGE_READWRITE = 4
    Note: Windows x86_64 page size is 4096 bytes from GetSystemInfo
    Let result be windows_x86_64_api_virtual_alloc(addr, 4096, 12288, 4)
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by HANDLE; not exposed in this file's Win32 api_* surface
    Note: Windows-native code uses kernel32!GetFileInformationByHandle via stdlib I/O
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file pointer; not exposed in this file's Win32 api_* surface
    Note: whence (0/1/2) is numerically compatible with FILE_BEGIN/FILE_CURRENT/FILE_END
    Note: Windows-native code uses kernel32!SetFilePointerEx via stdlib I/O
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "windows_x86_64_is_error" takes result as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if result indicates an error
    Note: result: result from Windows API call
    Note: Returns: 1 if error, 0 if success
    
    If result is equal to 0 or result is equal to windows_x86_64_INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_x86_64_get_error_message" takes error_code as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get error message for error code
    Note: error_code: Windows error code
    Note: Returns: error message string
    
    If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_SUCCESS:
        Return "Success"
    Otherwise If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_FILE_NOT_FOUND:
        Return "File not found"
    Otherwise If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED:
        Return "Access denied"
    Otherwise If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_INVALID_HANDLE:
        Return "Invalid handle"
    Otherwise If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_NOT_ENOUGH_MEMORY:
        Return "Not enough memory"
    Otherwise If error_code is equal to windows_x86_64_ERROR_INVALID_PARAMETER:
        Return "Invalid parameter"
    End If
    
    Return "Unknown error"
End Process